description: The curfew was prolonged once again. Now it lasts until July 12, 11 PM. However, a renewed prolongation was envisaged, probably until August. As before, citizens are only allowed to leave their house once in two weeks according to the last digit of their ID, from 7AM to 5PM. On weekends no one is allowed to leave. The plan of "intelligent reopening" of the economy is continued everywhere, but not in Tegucipalpa (Central District) and San Pedro Sula. As before, the degree of reopening depends along three regions with region 3 being the strictest. A new regulation is that in region 3, only cars with a pair / impair licence plate are allowed alternately. It is unclear whether someone would be allowed to leave if his ID would allow him/her to, but his licence plate doesn't. Region 3 consists of: El Progreso, Tegucigalpa, La Lima, Villanueva, San Manuel, Puerto Cortés, Potrerillos, Pimienta, Choloma, San Pedro Sula, Nueva Arcadia, Siguatepeque, La Ceiba, El Triunfo, Goascorán, Juticalpa, Nacaome, Namasigüe, Omoa, Pespire, Quimistán, Sabanagrande, San Francisco de Yojoa, San Lorenzo, Choluteca, Santa Lucía, Valle de Ángeles, Santa Rosa de Copán, Tocoa, and Trujillo. description:
Honduras extends the absolute curfew until May 17. Residents are only allowed to go to grocery shops, pharmacies, hardware shops, gas stations, and banks on one day in two weeks depending on the last digit of their ID. On Saturdays and Sundays everything stays closed and no one is allowed to leave their houses. Exceptions are only made for indispensable workers (transport, health, and agrifood sectors).

description: On May 6, the Honduran government announced a (renewed) absolute curfew for the Cortés district as well as for the municipalities of El Progreso, Yoro and Las Vegas, Santa Bárbara; The absolute curfew in these places had been in place before, was relaxed in the meanwhile, but now it is set back in force from May 6 until May 10. Unlike in other parts of the country, no one is allowed to leave their house for buying food or medicine. Just home delivery is allowed for supermarkets, grocery shops and pharmacies. Delivery is allowed for small shops ("pulperías") between 7AM and 8PM and for supermarkets and pharmacies from 7AM to 5PM. The transport, agriculture, and health sectors are allowed to run normally (with enforced hygiene measures), all other businesses are not allowed to open. Entrance roads to the named provinces/municipalities are controlled.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date

description:
The curfew was prolonged until June 14, but most sectors are allowed to reopen. Citizens remain to be allowed to circulate only one day in 2 weeks according to the last digit of their ID from 7AM to 5 PM, except for working in allowed workplaces. From 7AM to 9AM all businesses are open only to the elderly, pregnant, and handicapped, also according to the last digit of their ID.

A percentage of the population is allowed to return to their workplaces. There are three different regions depending on the number of infections in the respective municipality.

In region 3, only 20% of the usual workforce is allowed to work again. Region 3 comprises of the municipalities of La Ceiba, Siguatepeque, Nueva Arcadia, San Pedro Sula, Choloma, Pimienta, Potrerillos, Puerto Cortés, San Manuel, Villanueva, La Lima, Distrito Central and El Progreso

 In region 2, 40% of the usual workforce is allowed to work. Region 2. For a list of municipalities, see the source. Actually, the entry was cut here as it was too long. Description of region 1 is missing, but you find it in the source

Still closed: Public transport, bars, night clubs, cinemas, gyms, theatres, sporting venues, congress centers, airports, education facilties. Honduras closed all borders (air, land, and sea) on March 15, 2020 for seven days. Borders remain open for the transport of goods.

UPDATE: As of July, borders are still regularly closed for persons. The only ones allowed to enter the territory are Honduran nationals, permanent and temporary residents and accredited diplomats. These groups need to quarantine at home immediately after entering Honduras. Borders were never closed for transport of goods.

It consists of two facilities with a combined capacity of 300 people, where migrants must pass through upon arrival in Honduras. They will receive three meals daily, free medical and psychological care, biosecurity supplies, and constant review for detecting COVID-19 symptoms. description: On March 29, 2020, the Honduran National Police announced that, starting March 30, 2020 until at least April 12, 2020, the Honduran people would be segmented by the last number of their ID card. Those whose card ended in 4, 5, or 6 could go out on Wednesdays from 9 am to 3 pm to get food, medicine, gas, and go about their natural processes. Those whose card ended in 7, 8, 9, and 0 could go out on Fridays from 9 am to 3 pm to get food, medicine, gas, and go about their natural processes. Members of SINAGER, the agroindustrial supply chain, old people, pregnant women and those with a salvoconducto are exempt from this measure.

description:
In Honduras, the national government approved a four stage plan for a revival of the construction sector on May 19. Construction companies will resume working on roads, bridges, housing projects, airports, and projects that suddenly stopped when the pandemic began. The stages/weeks:
1. Construction of the Palmerola airport and Las Flores-Comayagua highway (already began after May 4 measures were announced)
2. projects that employ 150 or more workers
3. projects that employ more than 50 people
4. projects that employ less than 50 people
In each phase the Chamber of Construction and College of Civil will ensure that biosafety protocols are followed.

description: Honduras has implemented a smart economic and social reopening plan which begins June 1. It will begin with phase zero, the preparation stage, from June 1-7. During this week companies must prepare their biosafety protocols which were authorized by the Ministry of Labor and Social Security on May 4. The plan is to then open on June 8 after preparations are finished. Cities will be put into one of 3 regions based on their number of cases. Based on this they will have a 3-5 stage reopening plan. During this time when people are found on the streets without authorization they will still be punished in accordance with the law and companies not complying with protocols will be closed for 90 days. All open businesses can only be open from 7am-5pm, and local curfews are still in effect.

description:
In Honduras, as part of the smart reopening plan they country was divided into 3 regions which go through a five phase plan - their starting point pithing the phases depends on the amount of cases they have. Region 3, with the most cases, will begin phase 1 on June 8. This means they will have 20% of the workforce returning. If there are spikes in cases they will move to phase 2, with 40% of the workforce returning to work, in 2 weeks.

The Central District, which previously began phase 1 on June 8, had to revert to phase 0 on June 21 due to a spike in cases. Only workers in preapproved markets were exempted from the reversal. description: The Honduras judiciary has suspended work from March 23-March 29 and deemed those days as "unusual" for the purposes of proceedings and procedural deadlines. Most essential personnel will telework, however essential personell who are required to be physically at work, including limited people of the courts that deal with criminal matters, children, and domestic violence will be at work on a rotational bases. Personnel will only go into work to deal with matters of extreme urgency and to receive paperwork such as the delivery of alimony. Pregnant women, people over age 60, people with immune deficiencies, or other at risk diseases will not be allowed to rotate into work. All scheduled hearings during these dates will be rescheduled.

description: The Honduran president issued an executive order for more than 70 state institutions, especially those that generate income, to present their smart reopening plan in order to open asap. In their reopening plans they must outline how they will apply all requires biosafety protocols. Employees are expected to return to work, but there are exceptions for people over age 60, pregnant women, cancer or cancer treatment patients, and people with hypertension, diabetes, or kidney disease. In the reopening plan each institution must give the name and address of employees who will be returning to work. It also must include a number of people who live with them. Institutions must also follow the 10-4 rule: they will work for 4 days and are off for 10 days to ensure they do not have symptoms.

description: The National Congress of Honduras passed the Mandatory Use of Masks and the Application of Biosafety Protocols law effective May 19 which requires everyone, without exception, to wear a mask or face covering when they are in public places or when in private places where more than 5 people are present. Non compliance will result in a fine of 200 Lempiras or mandatory community work for 6 hours. Recidivism results in 24 hours of detention, and repeated recidivism will result in an end to their benefits from governmental social programs.
date_end_spec: The policy’s end date is unknown or unreported
type_sub_cat: Wearing Masks in all public spaces/everywhere
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries

description: Honduras enforces a restriction and regulation of business. The Secretary of State in the Security Office will authorize the reopening of shops and companies in general. However, the following are excluded from the reopening: urban and interurban public transport, bars, discotheques, cinemas, gyms, theaters, sporting events, convention center, airport, educational centers at primary, secondary, and higher levels; Nor is it allowed to hold meetings in private homes of more than 10 people, beginning on June 8, 2020.
